cs.CV, cs.MM, cs.LG, cs.HC, cs.IR 

This paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with activity classification in security video. It also involves machine learning techniques for performance evaluation, which makes it likely to belong to the Machine Learning (cs.MM) and Learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. The use of crowdsourcing for data collection and annotation makes it relevant to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category. Finally, the use of scenario acting strategy and performance evaluation on VIRAT Ground 2.0 dataset makes it relevant to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category.
